		<section2 id="sExamples">
			<secTitle>Conventions used in the examples</secTitle>
			<p>
				<content>This grammar contains many illustrative phrases and sentences.  Most of these are presented in an interlinear format consisting of three or four lines, as shown in </content>
				<exampleRef num="xEx"/>
				<content>:</content>
			</p>
			<example num="xEx">
				<table>
					<row>
						<col>
							<content>[vernacular words]</content>
						</col>
						<col>
							<langData>word</langData>
						</col>
						<col>
							<langData>word</langData>
						</col>
						<col>
							<langData>word</langData>
						</col>
					</row>
					<row>
						<col>
							<content>[literal word glosses]</content>
						</col>
						<col>
							<content>gloss</content>
						</col>
						<col>
							<content>gloss</content>
						</col>
						<col>
							<content>gloss</content>
						</col>
					</row>
					<row>
						<col>
							<content>[morpheme glosses]</content>
						</col>
						<col>
							<content>PRE-root-SUF</content>
						</col>
						<col>
							<content>PRE-root-SUF</content>
						</col>
						<col>
							<content>PRE-root-SUF</content>
						</col>
					</row>
					<row>
						<col>
							<content>[free translation]</content>
						</col>
						<col colspan="3">
							<content>free translation phrase or sentence</content>
						</col>
					</row>
				</table>
			</example>
			<p>
				<content>The words in </content>
				<langName/>
				<content> are given on the first line.  The second line presents a literal translation in English, word for word, giving the English word gloss that is the closest in meaning to the word in </content>
				<langName/>
				<content>.  If more than one English word is needed to express the meaning of the </content>
				<langName/>
				<content> word, these English words will be separated by periods.  Whenever one or more of the </content>
				<langName/>
				<content> words has more than one part (morpheme), the third line shows the glosses for the parts of the word, with the prefixes, root, and suffixes separated by hyphens.  This third line may be most useful to linguists.  The final line gives the free translation for the whole example.</content>
			</p>
			<p>
				<comment>Say more here about  any differences between your language and English.  For example, if your language does not distinguish between number and/or gender on nouns, but the gloss language does, you choose to use only singular and/or masculine forms for the glosses.</comment>
			</p>
			<p>
				<content>After giving information on the syntactic typology of the language, the grammar begins by describing the parts of speech and the phrases they head in sections </content>
				<sectionRef sec="sN"/>
				<content> - </content>
				<sectionRef sec="sExcl"/>
				<content>.  Basic, main clause sentences are then covered in section </content>
				<sectionRef sec="sIP"/>
				<content>, followed by constructions involving changes in word order (sections </content>
				<sectionRef sec="sFocus"/>
				<content> - </content>
				<sectionRef sec="sNeg"/>
				<content>).  Coordination constructions are then covered in section </content>
				<sectionRef sec="sCoord"/>
				<content>, followed finally by various types of embedded clauses (sections </content>
				<sectionRef sec="sComp"/>
				<content> - </content>
				<sectionRef sec="sRelCl"/>
				<content>).  Some texts are included at the end to demonstrate how larger constructions such as paragraphs, conversations, and narrative stories are formed.</content>
			</p>
		</section2>
